July 17. 1866. Elysia? Tuesday eve?.
My dearest
I have just written a letter to Rev J. Newten? in reply to one from him asking for coal. Last night wrote one to L.L. Jenkins in reply to one from him. He is established at Boston you know. Your letter of the 13th came to hand this evening. The Boys and myself wrote a big letter to you Sunday night, mailed yesterday morning, which after some hesitation I directed ampersand? unclear; thinking it would not get around before Thursday, and that by that time you would be there rather than at Yarmouth. I wrote much about going East, or rather not going, and mostly concluding it was hardly best to try to go. If i went I should hardly feel like staying more than the unclear possible days to go and come in, and perhaps it would hardly be months the while if you could come back alone or with Samuel or somehow. There would seems to be no difficulty about the Children,or about any one of them in particular at any rate. Unclear could go up to Charles'. or over to Mr. Luiss?, Charley to Dr. unclear or half a dozen other places; he has a first class unclear to go down to Boyds' on the Lake Shore. Unclear Boyd is an especial chum of his. Anna could stay at Luiss's? or anywhere else; would be good and right trouble anywhere; and Lucille? Don? John, could go to Eliale?, or Elisa could take
Completed

the best of care of him here. And yes somehow collectively I do not feel a bit like learning their/these?. Perhaps however I may start off in a unclear sunday, but it is very doubtful. Glad to hear of May's well doing. I must write to her dear self specially, I think. Look Anna tonight over to Mr. Luiss? by way of Experiment. Do not know how it will answer. Little John wanted "Nanny" "Nanny" very frequently after she was. I suspect he will be sort of lonesome and fretting for her. You speak of any weather for our unclear You need not say much now on that score. It cleared off here in Monday July 9th. Since then a cloudless sky, the heat will? the thermometer any where but ^ in the ice houses has ranged from 90 to 100, and the Drought already begins to be sense?! Tonight a few cloudy minutes? and a bare sprinkle seem to have cooled the air a little.
unclear Isaac.
Completed

Isaac July 19 1866 Elysia, July 19 1866 My Dearest Your letter to Charley came to hand tonight. Charley & Milder? had gone over to Mr Luiss'? to see Emma to carry her some clothes or lead her home as might be. She went over there on Tuesday P.M. I should not see the boys, as it was meeting night until tomorrow morning. So I thought I might as well read the letter myself. And now perhaps I may as well answer it.Thought I do not know it it needs special answer, except that we are especially glad to have you write to us often and particularly.
Completed

It is comfortably cool for a day or two past, cloudy though with very little rain, just enough yesterday afternoon to wet my hay; the three acre meadow beyond the Renson? house was mowed by a morning machine yesterday morning. The sun did not come out and it did not dry enough to take? up and it got wet before night. Today the boys & myself, unclear worked unclear it most of the afternoon & Charles & his three boys
Completed

Meetings last merk?R & unclear before quite unclear. Tonight the room quite full and a very good meeting. Just six prayers and six exhortations, besides a few remarks of Mrs unclear. Charley will be greatly pleased at his letters, and Mildes? will make a comical face because he has not one. Rev Geo? unclear Perkins I very well remember. Though seeing his name occasionally of late I hardly knew of it was the same, slender, pale faced hard student. Do I understand that you wanted another picture of John tried for? Me? thought that was about right. Then are you going back from Penbroke? & Dunbarton?? Samuel left here this morning. I was sorry it happened so you were gone from Yarmouth, the
Completed

of this [?]sh and first of next. Samuel might have called at [?] if you had been to be there. I might have sent some money to you by him. You might have gone on with him to go to 
Brownsville to visit a [?]. As it is so [?] about my going on at all, or if I should [?] my stopping [?]. And judging from a letter Charles received from Almeda yesterday there is little or no [?] of her coming [?] this fall. She said she could [?] any [?] come with Samuel for she could not at all [?] in hot weather. And the state of [?]'s (James' wife's) health was such it was very dreadful if she could leave at all. She is [?] [?] with consumption I guess.Sincerely, Isaac.
Completed

Elyria, July 22 1866
Very Dearest
Yours of the 18th inst came to hand last night. Your letters seem to come this way quicker than ours get to you do they not. I do not understand from your letter just how long you are going to stay in New Hampshire - especially unclear the new arrangement - as George does not go with you. It seems to have happened just wrong in some respects about the time of your going to New Hamp He was solo-unclear about unclear to you by Samuel. He left here for Maine the same day your letter that came last night was written Wednesday 18th, if you were at Yarmouth he would have called there. I intend to send some money to you by him. It would have been a good chance for you to go to see Almeda with him. That is, if you had better go there. It seems that Almeda is not at all likely to come visit any time soon: As I have written to you, she cannot come in warm weather, and James' wife is sick and there is evidently like provability that she will be able to leave her. I judged from somewhat you wrote or said that if Almeda was not coming to Ohio this season you should want to visit her. If Samuel had called at Yarmouth while you were there you could have gone
Completed

right down to Bangor & Brownville with him. 
However it will all be right somehow, and it was unavoidable as there was no way of presuing the matter. Samuel I think will write you after he get to Bangor or Somewhere, and perhaps he may yet be some censenience in helping you to get there if you should think it best to try to do so. 
To go to Brownville you would have to go to Bangor on afternoon, stay over night there, and the next day have a long hard ride by Stage Coach 40 miles or more to Brownville, And at Brownville you know they live 5 miles away off over the hills and far away. Though if they knew what day to expect you they would be down to the village to meet you doubtless. I doubt if it is worth your while to unclear to go there at all this summer - at any rate - if you have to go alone. Samuel took him him that large carpet Jack unclear filled with things for Almeda, Large Photographs in frame, she had Bibles for James & Lizzy, and sunday dresses &c. What Anna picked out, or gave to me to pack.
I do not yet decide hardly what to do about going to Maine after you. If I should go I should not feel like stopping at all, or hardly. What time do you want to come home if I do not come after you? Perhaps you could come with Samuel when he and his wife come back which will be some time in August, he hardly knew when when here. I suppose the difficulty of coming home alone from
Completed

Yarmouth would be no more than of going there alone and much less than of going from there to New Hampshire or to Bangor. Perhaps you could get George or some one to come to Boston with you, if you chose. You say if you came to Maine, your anxiety would be only for the boys. I do not know as I should feel much anxiety about them. They are really pretty good boys. Wilder especially is in unusually good health for him. He would I think be a good boy and do well wherever he was left. Charley has not improved in health and strength this summer as Wilder has. Appetite is more irregular, is more fretful etc. etc. But he would be a good boy anywhere and Anna is exceeding good and very little trouble anywhere. And as for unclear unclear, Eliza gets along first rate with him. And yet I do not seem to dare to leave them. Eliza does not know at all what to do with them if they are sick. If is to to be, or to be going a sickly season you know. They are all nice and well now - perhaps unusually so - but I keep thinking, 'what if they should be sick and neither of us with them.
I will send you some money in the next letter. This one will be mailed tomorrow morning before Bank hours. By the way Elyria is to be next month a money order Post Office, which will be quite convenient. I believe there is no Bank in Yarmouth is there.
Completed

Mr Wilber preached Today, very good, rather for him odd sermon. "Let your moderation [underlined]  be known to all men." Audience quite large - some out of town, but many visitors. Weather here was most excessively warm from the 10th to the 18th of July, perfectly dry also. Since then a little cooler mostly cloudy and with some rain. The "heated term" surpassed almost anything previously experienced here. Eliza & Wilder are gone to meeting this evening. While I stay with the children. Eliza goes to meeting monday evenings & I Thursday. I will write again in a day or two. Sincerely Isaac
Completed

Elyria, Monday Eve
July 23d 1866
Written sideways:
Isaac July 23
1866
Dearest
I mailed an epistle to you this morning, but it being before Bank hours, {the letter was written on Sunday}, I could not enclose my money. To day I have purchased a New York Draft for fifty dollars which I will enclose herewith. Our money order office (P.O. Money Order) will not be running till next month comes in.
This Draft will not be much trouble to you. I was almost inclined to send Bank Bills in a letter but this is safer; and if there is no Bank at Yarmouth you can easily get it cashed. Perhaps George can give you the money and, get it cashed when he goes to Portland, and give you the money, or probably any merchant or trader at Yarmouth will cash it for you. You will need to write your name across the back of the Draft, just as mine is. -- Simply your name if it goes right into Bank, Order & name (as it is now) if you want it paid to any one else.
Finish haying today - got in my meadow mowed unfortunately last Wed. the day the heated storm broke up. somewhat injured by the weather.
Eliab & Maria talk of going to Pennsylvania the same trip you & I took two years ago. Start next week, be gone some time; talk of taking two of the
Completed

children with them I think, Lucy and unclear. When do you mean to come home? All things considered, I have about come to the conclusion that I better not go after you, that is always if you think you can come alone well enough and think it best to.
If I do not you will of course stay just as long as you think best. We are getting along unclear and can all summer. If you are gaining in health & strength and fat & spirits &c. &c. and May also, there where you feel the fresh salt ocean water breezes every day. You had perhaps better stay and keep doing so.l
It may be for your health to stay there all through the hot weather. We can get along first rate without you - or if we should be sick or any thing the matter we could telegraph to you and you know it in an hour or two any time.
If you want more money, I can send it any time whenever you want. Let me know how much you have and write often & fully
ISMetcalf
Your
Isaac
Completed

Isaac
July 25 1866
Elyria July 25 1866
Dearest Nettie
Yours of the 20th came to hand last night and assured us of your safe arrival at Pembroke I mailed either two or three letters to you directed Pembroke, then since to Yarmouth again I did not know how long you would remain in New Hampshire. Perhaps one of them George may remail to you at Dunbarton, otherwise you may be at Dunbarton a week without any letter.
But we are all right here, whether
Completed

you hear from us or not.
I did send no pictures to you or any one by Samuel because you not being at Yarmouth when Samuel went, he would not call there.
We have got no new pictures If I do not go East to meet you, perhaps we had better let it wait. They can be sent in a letter as will after to return and get there to unclear your self as before.
Your sharp eyed conductor will chg 1/2 fare for May, is a Conductor who puts such things on his own pocket instead of the R.R.
Completed

I should like to see Mr Willey as unclear as many others you have seen or will see.
I mailed a letter to Yarmouth yesterday enclosing a Draft for $50.00 payable to yr order. If you want more let me know Have all you want. Buy any thing you want that you think you can get on better terms there than here.
Absolutely yrs
Isaac
Completed

Isaac July 27 1866
Elyria, July 27 1866
unclear Nettie
Yours of the 23rd mailed at Concord 24th came to hand last night. Glad to hear of your well doing - expect you are enjoying a fine lot of visiting around old Dunbarton nowadays this week. Ought to have mailed a letter on time to reach you there, but did not send them to Yarmouth not knowing when or how long you would be elsewhere. Presume I should 
this line covered by a fold in the paper
Your folks there I like especially well. E.G. Sue Parker, Capt Whipple, Safford, Chaz Rider.
Nothing special to communicate here. Yesterday P.M. 4 oclock, took horse & buggy & took children to ride - John & Anna & drove up to Charles' where Wilder & Charley were making hay very smartly. (Had a mowing machine at work & plenty of business for small rakers, Percy there too), took the boys in and drove around slightly. The Boys are told they shall go to the lake again after you get home. So they have an especial hurry for you to come on that additional cause.
Completed

Children all smart & well.
John improving daily in sleep & conduct. Meeting last eve full & strong
Rev Theodore Holmes of SA. Hartford expected to preach here next Sabbath
Dr DuWitt & Anna here a minute last eve before meeting.
Eliab & Maria out riding called also.
Miss people at Charles yesterday P.M.
Completed

Sideways:
Isaac
July 29 1866
Elyria, July 29, 1866
Dearest
We did not get any letter from you yesterday, and none from Dunbarton; wherefor Mrs unclear & Mrs unclear enquired at Church. No letter came, but Mary Barbor did come arriving from Sandusky on the afternoon train However joyfully she might be welcomed, it is suspected by the cynical that a letter from yourself might have been equally welcome. Miss Barber attended a Prayer Meeting at the Baptist Church this forenoon I understand. However she was not especially missed at the unclear Church, where a quite full house was assembled to hear the Rev Theodore Holmes of East Hartford, who preached to beautiful acceptance, and also addressed the Sabbath School and also the infant class. Mr Holmes is quite a handsome young man, appearing some 10 or 15 yrs under his reputed age, rather short but quite muscular with a bright sharp blue eye. I imagine he will take well, though perhaps not very much of a preacher, but evidently an energetic nice man.
Completed

Children are all finely.
Little Don John is in fine health feels better and sleeps better I think than he has since you went away. Little Anna of course frets occasionally in the very not weather, but I think John is getting acclimated to the extreme hot weather and it agrees with him better than with Fan Anna.
The boys, as well as Percy have worked haying up to Uncle Charles the past week some. Haying is finished now.
When are you coming home? Do not hurry yourself. We are all getting on first rate. And all probably prefer that you should stay where you are if cooler more comfortable and gaining in health & strength both of you - much as of course we should like to see you and have you at home. Charley says wont she come this week? We have done well constantly in your absence fared sumptuously every day, and I have not perceived in my self or the children any sort of lack or suffering for washing or mending. In fact I am afraid it is demonstrated that what ever we may have thought heretofore, even your precious self is not absolutely essential to the existence of the household. If you want more money I will send it any time. Next week we can have P.O. Money orders. You will want more money if you have chance to go shopping. Otherwise not perhaps.
Completed

Isaac
July 31 1866
Elyria July 31 1866
Dearest
Your letter of the 26th came to hand last night.
I am sorry about your not getting letters at Dunbarton. If I had been a little brighter might perhaps have thought better, and directed a letter or two there instead of to So Yarmouth after two to Pembroke. However perhaps George remailed one or two from Yarmouth.
I expect you are back at Yarmouth again by this time, and find a lot of letters waiting you there.
Completed

We are all in fine health and spirits. John and Anna space? about at a great rate. Mary Barber makes her ? generally useful I judge. Washing dishes this morning while Eliza was getting to ?ning. Eliah ? do not go to ? till next week. He has ? ones or work on his new ? and ? leave them Mr. Holmes goes back to ? Friday. Lee ? our house Friday. Blackberries begin to ripen. Also green corn to ?.

Write frequently. If you want more money I will send you a P.O. money order next week. Sincerely, Isaac.
